Kim Jong Il inspects Youth Hero Motorway 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 14 (KCNA) -- General Secretary Kim Jong Il inspected newly-built Youth Hero Motorway on Monday. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 When Kim Jong Il appeared at the entrance to the motorway, members of the youth shock brigade and soldier-builders enthusiastically welcomed him, breaking into thunderous cheers of "hurrah ".  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
The 40-odd km-long modern motorway from the fork at Mangyongdae, Pyongyang, to the youth bridge at the entrance to Nampho, is a gift presented by members of the youth shock brigade and servicemen with loyalty to the 55th anniversary of the WPK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 This modern motorway is wide enough for several vehicles to run at a time. It has unique bridges and crossings. There appeared on its either side green belts and woodlands and houses for thousands of families. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Kim Jong Il acquainted himself in detail with the construction of the motorway, looking round wide highway, flyovers of particular style, green belts and houses on either side of the motorway. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Saying that the motorway has been impeccably built in terms not only of its width and blueprint but of all its structures, he stressed that the heroic struggle and enduring feats of the young builders will shine long in the history of building a powerful socialist nation and their immortal feats will be always remembered by the country and the people. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He noted that members of the youth shock brigade and young soldier-builders wrought such miracles as building a great edifice of eternal value with empty hands in the revolutionary spirit of soldiers, the revolutionary spirit of devotedly carrying out any task when the country was under the most difficult conditions. This signal achievement is a demonstration of the great mental power of the Korean youth who like to work and make revolution, he said. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Praising the young Koreans as the militant vanguard and shock brigade of the revolution that registered victories, braving the hardships and difficulties hard to endure, he said: It is the great pride of the Worker's Party of Korea and the Korean people to have such excellent youth and the Korean revolution is sure to win as the ranks of those proud young loyalists are giving steady continuity to the revolution. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The youth hero motorway should be put into better shape and always kept clean and neat as it is a precious wealth to be handed down to posterity, he said. He advanced highly important tasks that would serve as guidelines in managing and operating the motorway. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He met and gave warm pep-talks to the youth shock brigade members and soldier-builders who performed heroic feats in the construction of the motorway and posed for a picture with them. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Accompanying him were director of the general political department of the Korean People's Army Jo Myong Rok, chief of the KPA general staff Kim Yong Chun, Minister of the People's Armed Forces Kim Il Chol, member of the DPRK National Defence Commission Yon Hyong Muk, secretaries of the WPK Central Committee Han Song Ryong, Kim Kuk Thae, Kim Jung Rin and Kim Yong Sun, secretary of the presidium of the Supreme People's Assembly Kim Yun Hyok, department directors and first vice department directors and other leading officials of the WPK Central Committee, and KPA generals Hyon Chol Hae and Pak Jae Gyong.

Kim Jong Il inspects newly-built Hwangju chicken factory 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 14 (KCNA) -- General Secretary Kim Jong Il yesterday gave on-the-spot guidance to the Hwangju chicken factory newly built by servicepersons. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The factory with a total floor space of more than 27,000 square metres has been built under a far-reaching plan of Kim Jong Il. It is a modern factory where all processes and temperature, humidity and lighting regulation are computerized. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Looking round the outside and inside of the factory reminiscent of a modern scientific research center, Kim Jong Il was much pleased to learn that soldier-builders completed it in such a short span of time. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He highly appreciated their feats and expressed thanks, noting that by the heroic struggle of servicemen one more edifice of eternal value was built to bring prosperity to the country. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Underscoring the need to pay primary attention to technical control and the management of equipment as it is a highly automated ultra modern factory, he urged its officials and workers to steadily improve their technical skills and thus manage and operate it on a scientific basis. After looking round the factory he put forward important tasks to bring about a decisive turn in the improvement of the standard of people's living by putting stock-breeding onto a new stage. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
  Calling for building ultra modern and highly productive chicken,  duck,  goose and pig factories  in different parts of the country under a long-term plan, he stressed that all factories to be built should be completed so impeccably that they may be handed down to posterity. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He underscored the need to thoroughly establish a feed supply system and thus make the existing stock-breeding bases pay off and build a strict anti-epidemic system in all domains of stock-breeding including poultry industry. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He was accompanied by Jo Myong Rok, director of the general political department of the KPA= Kim Yong Chun, chief of the general staff of the KPA= Kim Il Chol, Minister of the People's Armed Forces= Yon Hyong Muk, member of the DPRK National Defence Commission= and KPA generals Hyon Chol Hae and Pak Jae Gyong. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He was also accompanied by Han Song Ryong, Kim Kuk Thae, Kim Jung Rin and Kim Yong Sun, secretaries of the WPK Central Committee, Kim Yun Hyok, secretary of the presidium of the Supreme People's Assembly, senior officials of the WPK Central Committee including department directors and first deputy department directors of the WPK Central Committee and Pak Nam Gi, chairman of the State Planning Commission.

Italian Minister of Industry and Foreign Trade arrives 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 14 (KCNA) -- Italian Minister of Industry and Foreign Trade Enrico Letta and his party arrived here today. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They were greeted at the airport by Kim Pong Ik, vice-Minister of Foreign Trade, and officials concerned.

Australian Foreign Minister arrives 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 14 (KCNA) -- Alexander John Gosse Downer, Foreign Minister of Australia, and his party arrived here today. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They were greeted at the airport by Pak Kil Yon, vice-Minister of Foreign Affairs, and officials concerned. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Foreign Minister Paek Nam Sun today met and had a talk with the Foreign Minister of Australia and his party.

Talks held between foreign  ministers of DPRK and  Australia 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 14 (KCNA) -- Talks were held between DPRK Foreign Minister Paek Nam Sun and his Australian counterpart Alexander John Gosse Downer at the Mansudae Assembly Hall today. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 At the talks both sides exchanged views on the need to develop the friendly relations between the two countries and a series of issues of mutual concern.

Computerized library 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 14 (KCNA) -- A "computerized library" in Wonsan, the DPRK, draws many visitors. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Though it is not a large one, it is computerized to fully meet the needs of visitors. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Several computers are always ready to serve the readers. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The computers provide necessary information to them. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Linked with a computer network of the centers for the dissemination of science and technology across the country, the library can search and get necessary information from the Grand People's Study House, the Central Scientific and Technological Information Agency and the invention bureau of the Academy of Sciences in Pyongyang, etc. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Printing service for readers is also available at the library. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The computer network helps search and get files of books and information in the library. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 For this good service the library enjoys ever greater popularity among readers.

Cooperation between DPRK and Russia 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 14 (KCNA) -- An agreement on cooperation in the fields of standard, measuring and quality between the Measuring and Quality Supervisory  Bureau of the DPRK and the State Committee for Standardization and Measuring  of Russia was signed in Moscow on November 8. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Present at the signing ceremony were members of the "bureau delegation of the DPRK headed by director Kim Hyong Chol and Gennadi Voronin, chairman of the committee of Russia,  and others.

Pomminryon secretary general helps builders 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, November 14 (KCNA) -- Rim Min Sik, secretary general of the joint secretariat of the National Alliance for the Country's Reunification (Pomminryon), visited the site of construction of the monument to the three-point charter of national reunification yesterday. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He gave pep-talks to the builders while working with them. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He said that the Korean nation would hand down the immortal exploits of the respected President Kim Il Sung who had conducted energetic activities for national reunification until the last moments of his great life, from generation to generation. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Noting that the gate of reunification is now being opened wide under the wise leadership of the great Kim Jong Il, he said that Pomminryon would conduct more vigorous activities for the reunification under the banner of the three-point charter of national reunification. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He conveyed to an official concerned a stone of high quality and aid materials presented by the Japan regional headquarters of Pomminryon.

Strengthened driving force for national reunification called for 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 14 (KCNA) -- Rodong Sinmun in an article today calls on all the Korean people to come out as one to strengthen the patriotic driving force for reunification. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The driving force for Korea's reunification is not any particular class or strata but the whole Korean nation, because national reunification is a work for all Koreans and their own job and it is the driving force of the nation that is capable of achieving reunification, the article notes, and goes on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Koreans cannot fulfil their responsibility and role of their own accord as the driving force for reunification for being such force. Members of the nation from all walks of life and various political forces should unite as one. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The great unity of the nation should be achieved strictly on the principle of national independence under the banner of patriotism, the banner of national reunification. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The driving force for reunification will grow immensely strong and Korean reunification, the cherished desire of the nation, will come earlier, when all Koreans in the north and south and overseas get united on the principle of national independence under the banner of patriotism and reunification.

WPK's line of attaching great importance to youth 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 14 (KCNA) -- The line of attaching great importance to the youth is a unique idea set out by the Worker's Party of Korea for the first time in history, says Rodong Sinmun yesterday in an article. Noting that particular attention is paid to this line in the DPRK, the article says: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The WPK attaches weighty importance to the youth as an important line to accomplish the revolutionary cause of Juche. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The article goes on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The great leader Kim Il Sung set forth this idea and the respected leader Kim Jong Il is developing the youth movement, true to his intention. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The slogan "Love the youth " represents the unshakable will of Kim Jong Il to accomplish the revolutionary cause of Juche, firmly believing in the youth and enhancing their role. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The validity and invincible vitality of the WPK's line of giving great importance to the youth were fully proved by the fact that the youth built 40 odd-km-long Youth Hero Motorway with empty hands during the "arduous march" and forced march, thus setting a good example of devotedly defending the party and the leader. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Referring to important tasks to implement this line in the DPRK, the article calls for exerting sustained great efforts for the education of the youth, giving prominence to the Kim Il Sung Socialist Youth League and further strengthening it. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The youth league in the DPRK is the most dignified and militant one in the world as it bears the august name of Kim Il Sung and enjoys the absolute trust of Kim Jong Il.

Significance of first free trade zone in Africa 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, November 14 (KCNA) -- Rodong Sinmun yesterday in a signed article described the establishment of the first free trade zone in Africa some time ago as an important step for the unity and development of the continent. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is the demonstration of the African people's will to keep pace with the trend of the era with their united efforts, stressed the article. Referring to the great significance of the establishment of the free trade zone, it said: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 First of all, it fully showed the practical ability of the Africans to build a prosperous, new Africa with their united strength. The African countries are taking an attitude of solving all problems with the united strength of the continent, ridding themselves of the past wrong conception that they have no other way but to rely on the west . &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is also of great significance because it will serve as stimulant for promoting the pan-African integration, not merely by giving impetus to increasing investment and trade in eastern and southern African common market. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Describing the establishment of the free trade zone as an important step for the African economic community, the article said that the tireless efforts of the African people to achieve the rehabilitation and development of the continent will bring about good result.

KCNA refutes false reports of some west European media 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 14 (KCNA) -- A television and newspaper of a west European country spread cock-and-bull stories that the DPRK is diverting international food aid to the army and some "privileged circles" and children are starving to death at "camps."&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Timed to coincide with this, some west European countries  are egging certain individual persons, who know nothing about the DPRK, on to urge international human rights organizations including amnesty international to "probe human rights situation in North Korea" in a bid to build up public opinion critical of it. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 What can not be overlooked is that all those reports and what individual persons said are identical to the anti-DPRK false propaganda conducted by anti-DPRK hostile forces in the past and obviously, one prepared speech was read by them. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 As already known, there has been strict transparency in the distribution of international food aid given to the DPRK by the international community since its start and this was objectively verified by several international and non-governmental organizations including the World Food Program active in the country. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 This notwithstanding, media of some west European countries and some individual persons came out all of a sudden to raise a hue and cry over the non-existent "diversion of food aid" and "death of children" despite this stark reality. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
This can not be construed otherwise than an affront to the international organizations and donor countries which have sincerely participated in the humanitarian aid to the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 What is more serious is that those individual persons, not content with the diatribe launched by them over "transparency in the use of aid," are slinging mud at the DPRK over "human rights issue" by citing false information provided by anti-DPRK hostile forces at a time when the normalization of relations between the DPRK and the west European countries is on the order of the day. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Undoubtedly, through this they seek a sinister political aim to disturb international humanitarian aid to the DPRK and drive a wedge in the normalization process between the DPRK and the west European countries. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Some media and anti-DPRK hostile forces of western Europe should drop the anachronistic way of thinking, face up to the realities and behave themselves.
